#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:89
msgid ""
"If you select \"Yes\" for \"Trusted\", any X-OTRS headers attached to an "
"incoming message are evaluated and executed. Because the X-OTRS header can "
"execute some actions in the ticket system you should only set \"Trusted\" to "
"\"Yes\" for known senders. X-OTRS-Headers are used by the <link linkend="
"\"adminarea-postmasterfilter\"> filter module </link> in OTRS. The X-OTRS "
"headers are explained <link linkend=\"table-of-x-otrs-headers\"> in this "
"table </link> in more detail. Any postmaster filter rules you'd have created "
"are executed even if \"Trusted\" is set to \"Yes\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:109
msgid ""
"The distribution of incoming messages can be controlled if they need to be "
"sorted by queue or by the content of the To: field. If \"Dispatching by "
"selected queue\" is selected for \"Dispatching\", all incoming messages will "
"be sorted into the specified queue. The address where the mail was sent to "
"is disregarded in this case.  If \"Dispatching by email To: field\" was "
"selected for \"Dispatching\", the system checks if a queue is linked with "
"the address in the To: field of the incoming mail. You can link an address "
"in the <link linkend=\"adminarea-emailaddresses\"> E-mail address management "
"</link> section of the admin area. If the address in the To field is linked "
"with a queue, the new message will be sorted into the linked queue. If no "
"link is found between the address in the To: field and queue then the "
"message is sorted into the \"Raw\" queue in the system, which is the <link "
"linkend=\"Ticket:Core::PostMaster:PostmasterDefaultQueue\"> "
"PostmasterDefaultQueue </link> after a default installation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:136
msgid ""
"All data for the mail accounts are saved in the OTRS database. The "
"<filename>otrs.PostMasterMailbox.pl</filename> script, which is located in "
"the <filename>bin</filename> directory of your OTRS installation, uses the "
"settings in the database and fetches the mail. You can execute <filename>./"
"bin/otrs.PostMasterMailbox.pl</filename> manually to check if all your mail "
"settings are working properly."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:145
msgid ""
"On a normal installation, the mail will be fetched every 10 minutes by the "
"<filename>postmaster_mailbox</filename> cron job. For further information "
"about modifying cron jobs, please refer to the <link linkend=\"cronjobs\"> "
"cron jobs </link> chapter."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><note><para>
#: en/email.xml:155
msgid ""
"When fetching mail OTRS deletes the mail from the POP or IMAP server. "
"There's no option to also keep a copy on the server. If you'd want to "
"achieve this, you'd probably best create forwarding rules on your mail "
"server. Please consult your mail server documentation for details."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/email.xml:165
msgid "Via command line program and e.g. procmail (otrs.PostMaster.pl)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:168
msgid ""
"If you can't use mail accounts to get the email into OTRS, the command line "
"program <filename>bin/otrs.PostMaster.pl</filename> might be a solution. It "
"takes the mails via STDIN and pipes them directly into OTRS. That means "
"email will be available in your OTRS system if the MDA (mail delivery agent, "
"e.g. procmail) executes this program."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:176
msgid ""
"To test <filename>bin/otrs.PostMaster.pl</filename> without MDA, execute the "
"command of the Script 7.1."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><screen>
#: en/email.xml:182
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"linux:/opt/otrs# cd bin\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs/bin# cat ../doc/sample_mails/test-email-1.box | ./otrs.PostMaster.pl\n"
"linux:/opt/otrs/bin#\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:189
msgid "<emphasis>Script 7.1. Testing PostMaster withouth MDA.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:193
msgid "If the email is shown in the QueueView, then your setup is working."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:197
msgid ""
"Procmail is a very common e-mail filter in Linux environments. It will be "
"installed on most systems. If not, have a look at the <ulink url=\"http://"
"www.procmail.org/\"><citetitle>procmail homepage</citetitle></ulink>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:203
msgid ""
"To configure procmail for OTRS (requires a procmail configured MTA, e.g.  "
"sendmail, postfix, exim or qmail), use the <filename>~otrs/.procmailrc.dist</"
"filename> file and copy it to <filename>.procmailrc</filename> and add the "
"lines of the Script 7.2."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><programlisting>
#: en/email.xml:211
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"SYS_HOME=$HOME\n"
"PATH=/bin:/usr/bin:/usr/local/bin\n"
"# --\n"
"# Pipe all email into the PostMaster process.\n"
"# --\n"
":0 :\n"
"| $SYS_HOME/bin/otrs.PostMaster.pl\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:222
msgid "<emphasis>Script 7.2. Configuring procmail for OTRS.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:226
msgid ""
"All email sent to the local OTRS user will be piped into <filename>bin/otrs."
"PostMaster.pl</filename> and then shown in your QueueView."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/email.xml:234
msgid "Fetching emails via POP3 or IMAP and fetchmail for otrs.PostMaster.pl"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:237
msgid ""
"In order to get email from your mail server, via a POP3 or IMAP mailbox, to "
"the OTRS machine/local OTRS account and to procmail, use <ulink url=\"http://"
"fetchmail.berlios.de/\">fetchmail</ulink>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><note><para>
#: en/email.xml:244
msgid "A working SMTP configuration on the OTRS machine is required."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:249
msgid ""
"You can use the <filename>.fetchmailrc.dist</filename> in the home directory "
"of OTRS and copy it to <filename>.fetchmailrc</filename>.  Modfiy/change it "
"for your needs (see the Example 7-1 below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><example><title>
#: en/email.xml:255
msgid ".fetchmailrc"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><example><para><programlisting>
#: en/email.xml:259
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#poll (mailserver) protocol POP3 user (user) password (password) is (localuser)\n"
"poll mail.example.com protocol POP3 user joe password mama is otrs\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:267
msgid ""
"Don't forget to set the .fetchmailrc to 710 (\"chmod 710 .fetchmailrc\")!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:271
msgid ""
"With the <filename>.fetchmailrc</filename> from the Example 7-1 above, all "
"email will be forwarded to the local OTRS account, if the command "
"<command>fetchmail -a</command> is executed. Set up a cronjob with this "
"command if you want to fetch the mails regularly."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/email.xml:280
msgid ""
"Filtering/dispatching by OTRS/PostMaster modules (for more complex "
"dispatching)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:284
msgid ""
"If you use the bin/otrs.PostMaster.pl or bin/otrs.PostMasterMailbox.pl "
"method, you can insert or modify X-OTRS header entries with the PostMaster "
"filter modules.  With the X-OTRS headers, the ticket system can execute some "
"actions on incoming mails, sort them into a specific queue, change the "
"priority or change the customer ID, for example. More information about the "
"X-OTRS headers are available in the chapter about <link linkend=\"adminarea-"
"postmasterpop3-account\"> adding mail accounts </link> in the admin area of "
"OTRS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:299
msgid "There are some default filter modules:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><note><para>
#: en/email.xml:304
msgid ""
"The job name (e.g.  $Self-&gt;{'PostMaster::PreFilterModule'}-&gt;"
"{'JobName'}) needs to be unique!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:310
msgid ""
"Kernel::System::PostMaster::Filter::Match is a default module to match on "
"some email header (e.g. From, To, Subject, ...). It can set new email "
"headers (e.g. X-OTRS-Ignore: yes or X-OTRS-Queue: spam) if a filter rule "
"matches. The jobs of the Example 7-2 can be inserted in <filename>Kernel/"
"Config.pm</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><example><title>
#: en/email.xml:318
msgid ""
"Example jobs for the filter module Kernel::System::PostMaster::Filter::Match"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><example><para><programlisting>
#: en/email.xml:322
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    # Job Name: 1-Match\n"
"    # (block/ignore all spam email with From: noreply@)\n"
"    $Self-&gt;{'PostMaster::PreFilterModule'}-&gt;{'1-Match'} = {\n"
"        Module =&gt; 'Kernel::System::PostMaster::Filter::Match',\n"
"        Match =&gt; {\n"
"            From =&gt; 'noreply@',\n"
"        },\n"
"        Set =&gt; {\n"
"            'X-OTRS-Ignore' =&gt; 'yes',\n"
"        },\n"
"    };\n"
"    # Job Name: 2-Match\n"
"    # (sort emails with From: sales@example.com and Subject: **ORDER**\n"
"    # into queue 'Order')\n"
"    $Self-&gt;{'PostMaster::PreFilterModule'}-&gt;{'2-Match'} = {\n"
"        Module =&gt; 'Kernel::System::PostMaster::Filter::Match',\n"
"        Match =&gt; {\n"
"            To =&gt; 'sales@example.com',\n"
"            Subject =&gt; '**ORDER**',\n"
"        },\n"
"        Set =&gt; {\n"
"            'X-OTRS-Queue' =&gt; 'Order',\n"
"        },\n"
"    };\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:352
msgid ""
"Kernel::System::PostMaster::Filter::CMD is a default module to pipe the "
"email into an external command. The output is given to STDOUT and if the "
"result is true, then set new email header (e.g. X-OTRS-Ignore: yes or X-OTRS-"
"Queue: spam). The Example 7-3 can be used in <filename>Kernel/Config.pm</"
"filename>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><example><title>
#: en/email.xml:360
msgid ""
"Example job for the filter module Kernel::System::PostMaster::Filter::CMD"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><example><para><programlisting>
#: en/email.xml:364
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    # Job Name: 5-SpamAssassin\n"
"    # (SpamAssassin example setup, ignore spam emails)\n"
"    $Self-&gt;{'PostMaster::PreFilterModule'}-&gt;{'5-SpamAssassin'} = {\n"
"        Module =&gt; 'Kernel::System::PostMaster::Filter::CMD',\n"
"        CMD =&gt; '/usr/bin/spamassassin | grep -i \"X-Spam-Status: yes\"',\n"
"        Set =&gt; {\n"
"            'X-OTRS-Ignore' =&gt; 'yes',\n"
"        },\n"
"    };\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/email.xml:379
msgid ""
"Of course it's also possible to develop your own PostMaster filter modules."
