#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:18
msgid "OTRS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:20
msgid "There are several options to improve the performance of OTRS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:24
msgid "TicketIndexModule"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:26
msgid "There are two backend modules for the ticket index:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:34
msgid ""
"Kernel::System::Ticket::IndexAccelerator::RuntimeDB (default), generate each "
"queue view on the fly from the ticket table. You will not have performance "
"trouble until you have about 60,000 tickets (with 6,000 open tickets) in "
"your system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:42
msgid ""
"Kernel::System::Ticket::IndexAccelerator::StaticDB, the most powerful "
"module, it should be used when you have above 80,000 tickets (more than "
"6,000 open tickets) - it use an extra ticket_index table, which works like a "
"view. Use"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para><file>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:45
msgid "bin/otrs.RebuildTicketIndex.pl"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:46
msgid "for generating an initial index build after switching backends."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:54
msgid "You can change the IndexAccelerator via SysConfig."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:61
msgid "TicketStorageModule"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:63
msgid "There are two different backend modules for the ticket/article storage:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:71
msgid ""
"Kernel::System::Ticket::ArticleStorageDB (default), store attachments, etc.  "
"in the database. Note: Don't use it for large set ups."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:75
msgid ""
"Pro: If your webserver user isn't the otrs user, use this module to avoid "
"file permission problems."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:79
msgid ""
"Contra: It's not really advisable to store attachments in your database. "
"Take care that your database is able to store large objects. E.g. MySQL "
"(config)  \"set-variable = max_allowed_packet=8M\" to store 8 MB objects "
"(default is 2M)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:87
msgid ""
"Kernel::System::Ticket::ArticleStorageFS, store attachments etc. on the "
"local file system. Note: Recommended for large setups."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:91
msgid "Pro: Fast!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:94
msgid ""
"Contra: Your web server user should be the otrs user (file system "
"permissions!).  Also, if you have multiple front end servers, you should "
"make sure the file system is shared between the servers. So place it on an "
"NFS share or preferably a SAN or similar solution."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:106
msgid ""
"Note: you can switch from one to the other back-end on the fly. You can "
"switch the backend in the SysConfig, and then you can run the command line "
"utility <filename>otrs.ArticleStorageSwitch.pl</filename> to put the "
"articles from the database onto the filesystem or the other way around. You "
"can use the <emphasis>-s</emphasis> and <emphasis>-d</emphasis> option to "
"specify the source and destination back-ends. Please note that the whole "
"process can take a lot of time, depending on the amount of articles you have "
"and the available CPU power and/or network capacity."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><programlisting>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:118
#, no-wrap
msgid "shell> bin/otrs.ArticleStorageSwitch.pl -s ArticleStorageDB -d ArticleStorageFS\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:122
msgid ""
"<emphasis>Script 21.1 Switching storage back-ends from database to "
"filesystem.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:130
msgid "Database"
msgstr "Datenbank"

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:132
msgid ""
"This depends on the database you are using. If you're having trouble, read "
"the documentation for your database or ask your database administrator."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:137
msgid "MySQL"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:139
msgid ""
"If you use MySQL table type MyISAM (which is the default), and have deleted "
"a large part of a table or if you have made many changes to a table with "
"variable-length rows (tables that have VARCHAR, BLOB or TEXT columns), you "
"need to defragment the datafile (tables) with the \"optimize\" command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:145
msgid ""
"You should try this if mysqld needs a lot of your CPU time. Optimize tables "
"ticket, ticket_history and article (see Script 21.2 below)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><programlisting>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:151
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shell$ mysql -u user -p database\n"
"mysql$ optimize table ticket;\n"
"mysql$ optimize table ticket_history;\n"
"mysql$ optimize table article;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:159
msgid "<emphasis>Script 21.2. Optimizing data base tables.</emphasis>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:165
msgid "PostgreSQL"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:167
msgid ""
"PostgreSQL is best tuned by modifying the postgresql.conf file in your "
"PostgreSQL data directory. For advice on how to do this, see these articles:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:176
msgid ""
"<ulink url=\"http://www.revsys.com/writings/postgresql-performance.html\"> "
"<citetitle>http://www.revsys.com/writings/postgresql-performance.html</"
"citetitle> </ulink>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:183
msgid ""
"<ulink url=\"http://varlena.com/GeneralBits/Tidbits/perf.html\"> "
"<citetitle>http://varlena.com/GeneralBits/Tidbits/perf.html</citetitle> </"
"ulink>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para><itemizedlist><listitem><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:190
msgid ""
"<ulink url=\"http://varlena.com/GeneralBits/Tidbits/annotated_conf_e.html\"> "
"<citetitle>http://varlena.com/GeneralBits/Tidbits/annotated_conf_e.html</"
"citetitle> </ulink>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:199
msgid ""
"If performance is still not satisfactory, we suggest that you join the "
"PostgreSQL Performance mailing list ( <ulink url=\"http://www.postgresql.org/"
"community/lists/\"> http://www.postgresql.org/community/lists/ </ulink> ) "
"and ask questions there. The folks on the PostgreSQL list are very friendly "
"and can probably help."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:216
msgid ""
"Of course you should use mod_perl 2.0 ( <ulink url=\"http://perl.apache.org/"
"\"> <citetitle>http://perl.apache.org/</citetitle> </ulink>).  It's much "
"faster (~ * 100) than pure cgi. But it needs more RAM."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:224
msgid "Pre-establish database connections"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:226
msgid ""
"You can have the database connections pre-established on startup of the web "
"server.  This saves time (see README.webserver)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:232
msgid "Preloaded modules - startup.pl"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:234
msgid ""
"Use the startup script <filename>scripts/apache2-perl-startup.pl</filename> "
"for preloaded/precompiled Perl modules on your mod_perl webserver to be "
"faster and smaller (see README.webserver)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:239
msgid "Reload Perl modules when updated on disk"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:241
msgid ""
"By default Apachee::Reload is used in scripts/apache2-httpd.include.conf. "
"Disable it and you will get 8% more speed. But remember to restart the web "
"server if you install any modules via the OTRS Package Manager, any values "
"in your SysConfig or in Kernel/Config.pm.  Important: this would also mean "
"you can't use the OTRS Package Manager via the web interface, you need to "
"use the command line variant - <filename>bin/otrs.PackageManager.pl</"
"filename>."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:251
msgid "Choosing the Right Strategy"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:253
msgid ""
"If you have a really large installation (over 1,000 new tickets per day and "
"over 40 agents) it is a good idea to read \"Choosing the Right Strategy"
"\" (<ulink url=\"http://perl.apache.org/docs/1.0/guide/strategy.html\"> "
"<citetitle>http://perl.apache.org/docs/1.0/guide/strategy.html</citetitle> </"
"ulink>)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><title>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:262
msgid "mod_gzip/mod_deflate"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <chapter><section><section><para>
#: en/performance-tuning.xml:264
msgid ""
"If your bandwidth is a little bit small, use mod_deflate for Apache2.  If "
"you have an html page with 45k, mod_gzip/mod_deflate compresses it. The page "
"will be about 7k. The drawback is that this increases load on the server "
"side."
